Five truths about terrorism
SAO PAULO - American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism as the top issue facing the country - an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, even though their number is still far below the 46% recorded the day after the September 11, 2001, attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were especially felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians feel authorized to refer to the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But whose presidential candidates, as well as certain media outlets, enthusiasts of the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the proportions.
To put terrorism in its proper perspective, Americans should - like others - keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with grabbing attention and dominating the news than with the number of their victims, per se.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care of its staging.
The brutal beheadings broadcast on social media are intended to destabilize and outrage - and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every act of terrorism is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills far fewer people than road accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat — neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be killed by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans run a greater risk of dying in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from an accident caused by a household appliance (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), by a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving, texting or talking on their mobile phones.
It is hundreds of times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings in universities or schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to put out a terrorist outbreak.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, emerging from the "autonomous" left, diverted planes across national borders and kidnapped or killed business executives or political leaders (as well as ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon wrapped in a religious costume.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of IS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
IS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorist movements that preceded it have been.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking citizens of a state enough to drive them to futile actions, they can hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to draw Americans into Afghanistan.
IS was born from the ruins of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, it takes smart power.
A smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the military and police with the power of influence (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
The power of influence is also necessary if one wants to vaccinate those on the periphery and prevent the irreconcilables from recruiting them.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and how the actions of the United States are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important element of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and hooligans take place.
If we allow them to take over the grand stage of our public discourse, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and distort our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
